**Markdown to HTML Conversion Function**
======================================

Below is a C++ function that takes a `std::string` reference containing markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing HTML formatted text. This function uses the `markdown` library, which is a C++ implementation of the Markdown text-to-HTML conversion tool.

**Function Implementation**
-------------------------

```cpp
#include <markdown.h>
#include <string>

/**
 * Convert markdown formatted text to HTML.
 *
 * @param markdownText Reference to a std::string containing markdown formatted text.
 * @return A std::string containing HTML formatted text.
 */
std::string markdownToHtml(std::string& markdownText) {
    // Create a markdown document
    markdown::Document doc;
    doc.read(markdownText);

    // Render the markdown document to HTML
    std::string html;
    markdown::render(doc, markdown::HTMLRenderer(html));

    return html;
}
```

**Example Use Case**
-------------------

```cpp
int main() {
    std::string markdownText = "# Hello World\nThis is a paragraph.";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdownText);

    std::cout << html << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This example converts the markdown formatted text `# Hello World\nThis is a paragraph.` to HTML and prints the result to the console. The output will be:
```html
<h1>Hello World</h1>
<p>This is a paragraph.</p>
```

**Note**: You need to install the `markdown` library and include its headers in your project to use this function. The library can be installed via your package manager or by building it from source.

**Library Installation**

*   On Ubuntu-based systems: `sudo apt-get install libmarkdown-dev`
*   On macOS with Homebrew: `brew install markdown`
*   On Windows: Build the library from source using CMake and a C++ compiler.

Please ensure that you have the necessary dependencies installed and configured to use this function.

